","1367":"1367.","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1364":"1364.","1340":"1340.","1370":"1370.","1309":"1309","1438":"1438","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, England","Beverly,  Yorkshire,  ,  England":"Beverly, Yorkshire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1340–1370":"1340–1370","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1364–Female":"1364–Zesnulá","1370–1432":"1370–1432","1400–1437":"1400–1437","1314–Male":"1314–Zesnulý","1309–1367":"1309–1367","1437":"1437","1358":"1358","1314":"1314","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","1438":"1438","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, Anglie","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, Anglie","Beverly,  Yorkshire,  ,  England":"Beverly, Yorkshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1340–1370":"1340–1370","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1364–Female":"1364–Afdød","1370–1432":"1370–1432","1400–1437":"1400–1437","1314–Male":"1314–Afdød","1309–1367":"1309–1367","1437":"1437","1358":"1358","1314":"1314","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","1438":"1438","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, England","Beverly,  Yorkshire,  ,  England":"Beverly, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1340–1370":"1340–1370","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1364–Female":"1364–Overleden","1370–1432":"1370–1432","1400–1437":"1400–1437","1314–Male":"1314–Overleden","1309–1367":"1309–1367","1437":"1437","1358":"1358","1314":"1314","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","1438":"1438","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, England","Beverly,  Yorkshire,  ,  England":"Beverly, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1340–1370":"1340–1370","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1364–Female":"1364–Deceased","1370–1432":"1370–1432","1400–1437":"1400–1437","1314–Male":"1314–Deceased","1309–1367":"1309–1367","1437":"1437","1358":"1358","1314":"1314","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","1438":"1438","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, England","Beverly,  Yorkshire,  ,  England":"Beverly, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marshall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marchel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jacek, Ryszard.  German Ernst.","Polish: probably from French <i>maréchal</i> or Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>, which was originally an occupational name for someone who was in charge of the horses of a household, later a military rank for a senior general. See   Marshall   and compare   Marszalek  ."]},{"name":"Mercier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Gaston, Lucien, Aurele, Jacques, Normand, Laurent, Michel, Valmont.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): occupational name for a merchant, from Old French <i>mercier</i>, from Late Latin <i>merciarius</i> (an agent derivative of <i>merx</i>, genitive <i>mercis</i> ‘merchandise’). This name was also taken to England by Huguenot refugees. Compare   Marshall   and   Mercy  ."]},{"name":"Maniscalco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Vito, Sal, Antonio, Ignazio, Carmelo, Francesco, Gaspare, Saverio, Antonino, Carlo, Damiano.","Italian (southern): occupational name from <i>maniscalco</i> ‘farrier’, altered from <i>marescalco</i> by folk etymology, probably influenced by <i>mano</i> ‘hand’, from medieval Latin <i>mariscalcus</i>, <i>marescalcus</i>. Compare   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marchal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Jacques, Maryse, Philippe, Pierre, Veronique.","French and Walloon: status name or occupational name from Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The term is of ancient Germanic origin (from <i>marah</i> ‘horse, mare’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’) and was originally applied to a man who looked after horses. In the Middle Ages it also came to be used on the one hand as an occupational name for a farrier, and on the other as a status name for an officer of state, in particular a member of a royal household with military responsibilities. Compare English   Marshall   and 2 below.","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in Glamorgan, Wales."]},{"name":"Maskell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  , derived from Middle English, Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The first element in the placename Mascallsbury (Essex) derives from the surname of a 13th-century individual named Robert <i>le Marescal</i>."]},{"name":"Marszalek","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Piotr, Alicja, Andrzej, Eugeniusz, Henryk, Jerzy, Kazimierz, Mieczyslaw, Wieslaw, Zbigniew, Zofia, Zygmunt.","Polish (<b>Marszałek</b>): occupational or status name from the vocabulary word <i>marszałek</i> ‘marshal’, denoting anything from a high court official, a field marshal, or the chairman of the Polish parliament, to the senior servant in a great household. Compare English   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marshell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marschall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hedwig, Juergen, Reinhard, Theresia, Wilfried.","German: occupational name for a man in the service of a member of the nobility, originally one who looked after the horses, Middle High German <i>marschalc</i> (from <i>mar(c)</i> ‘noble horse’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant’). In time the term came to be used for a military rank or a certain court official. Compare   Marshall  .","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marshal","meanings":["(1997: 186;2007: 634; 2010: NA)","English and Scottish: variant of   Marshall  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Marshall Earl of Pembroke was born in 1340, in Hingham, Norfolk, England, his father, Sir William Marshall Earl of Pembroke, was 26 and his mother, Ann Empringham, was 31. He married Avis Anna Harden. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1370, in his hometown, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1340–1370":"1340–1370","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1364–Female":"1364–Surnud","1370–1432":"1370–1432","1400–1437":"1400–1437","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1309–1367":"1309–1367","1437":"1437","1358":"1358","1314":"1314","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","1438":"1438","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, England","Beverly,  Yorkshire,  ,  England":"Beverly, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1340–1370":"1340–1370","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1364–Female":"1364–Kuollut","1370–1432":"1370–1432","1400–1437":"1400–1437","1314–Male":"1314–Kuollut","1309–1367":"1309–1367","1437":"1437","1358":"1358","1314":"1314","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","1309":"1309","1438":"1438","Norbury, Derbyshire, England":"Norbury, Derbyshire, England","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, England","Beverly,  Yorkshire,  ,  England":"Beverly, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1340–1370":"1340–1370","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1364–Female":"1364–Décédée","1370–1432":"1370–1432","1400–1437":"1400–1437","1314–Male":"1314–Décédé","1309–1367":"1309–1367","1437":"1437","1358":"1358","1314":"1314","136